CMD vs ENTRYPOINT, ARG vs ENV
Part 1 — CMD vs ENTRYPOINT
The Core Difference

ENTRYPOINT = the executable that ALWAYS runs (cannot be overridden easily)
CMD        = default arguments passed to ENTRYPOINT (easily overridden at runtime)

Step 1 — CMD alone
# Dockerfile.cmd
FROM alpine
CMD ["echo", "hello from CMD"]

docker build -f Dockerfile.cmd -t test-cmd .

# Uses CMD as default
docker run --rm test-cmd
# hello from CMD

# CMD is REPLACED entirely when you pass args
docker run --rm test-cmd echo "overridden"
# overridden

docker run --rm test-cmd ls /
# bin  dev  etc  home ...   ← CMD completely replaced

Step 2 — ENTRYPOINT alone
# Dockerfile.ep
FROM alpine
ENTRYPOINT ["echo"]

docker build -f Dockerfile.ep -t test-ep .

# Runs echo with no args
docker run --rm test-ep
# (blank line)

# Args APPEND to ENTRYPOINT
docker run --rm test-ep "hello world"
# hello world

docker run --rm test-ep foo bar baz
# foo bar baz

Step 3 — ENTRYPOINT + CMD together (the correct pattern)
# Dockerfile.both
FROM alpine
ENTRYPOINT ["echo"]
CMD ["default message"]

docker build -f Dockerfile.both -t test-both .

# No args → uses CMD as default argument to ENTRYPOINT
docker run --rm test-both
# default message

# Override CMD only → ENTRYPOINT stays
docker run --rm test-both "custom message"
# custom message

# Override ENTRYPOINT entirely → use --entrypoint flag
docker run --rm --entrypoint ls test-both /etc
# hostname  hosts  passwd ...

Step 4 — Real-world pattern: script as ENTRYPOINT
# Dockerfile.real
FROM python:3.11-slim

WORKDIR /app
COPY app.py .

ENTRYPOINT ["python", "app.py"]
CMD ["--env", "production"]    # default args

# Production (uses CMD defaults)
docker run --rm test-real
# Running with --env production

# Override for dev
docker run --rm test-real --env development --debug
# Running with --env development --debug

# Override for testing
docker run --rm test-real --help
# Shows app help

Step 5 — Shell form vs Exec form (important!)
# SHELL form — runs via /bin/sh -c (BAD for signal handling)
CMD echo "hello"
ENTRYPOINT python app.py

# EXEC form — runs directly, PID 1, receives signals properly (GOOD)
CMD ["echo", "hello"]
ENTRYPOINT ["python", "app.py"]

# Prove the difference — check PID 1
docker run --rm test-shell ps aux
# PID 1 = /bin/sh -c python app.py  ← sh is PID 1, not your app
# SIGTERM goes to sh, NOT your app → graceful shutdown broken

docker run --rm test-exec ps aux
# PID 1 = python app.py  ← your app IS PID 1
# SIGTERM handled correctly → graceful shutdown works

Part 2 — ARG vs ENV
The Core Difference
ARG = build-time only — available during docker build, gone at runtime
ENV = runtime — available during build AND when container runs

Step 6 — ARG basics
# Dockerfile.arg
FROM alpine

ARG APP_VERSION=1.0.0        # default value
ARG BUILD_DATE

RUN echo "Building version $APP_VERSION on $BUILD_DATE"

CMD ["sh", "-c", "echo version is $APP_VERSION"]

docker build -f Dockerfile.arg -t test-arg .
# Building version 1.0.0 on    ← BUILD_DATE is empty (no default)

# Override ARG at build time
docker build -f Dockerfile.arg \
  --build-arg APP_VERSION=2.5.0 \
  --build-arg BUILD_DATE=$(date +%Y-%m-%d) \
  -t test-arg:2.5.0 .
# Building version 2.5.0 on 2026-06-11

# ARG is GONE at runtime
docker run --rm test-arg:2.5.0
# version is     ← empty! ARG doesn't exist at runtime

Step 7 — ENV basics
# Dockerfile.env
FROM alpine

ENV APP_ENV=production
ENV LOG_LEVEL=info
ENV DB_HOST=localhost DB_PORT=5432   # multiple on one line

CMD ["sh", "-c", "echo env=$APP_ENV log=$LOG_LEVEL db=$DB_HOST:$DB_PORT"]

docker build -f Dockerfile.env -t test-env .

# Uses Dockerfile defaults
docker run --rm test-env
# env=production log=info db=localhost:5432

# Override ENV at runtime with -e
docker run --rm -e APP_ENV=staging -e LOG_LEVEL=debug test-env
# env=staging log=debug db=localhost:5432

# Override with env file
cat > .env.local << EOF
APP_ENV=development
LOG_LEVEL=trace
DB_HOST=mydb.internal
EOF
docker run --rm --env-file .env.local test-env
# env=development log=trace db=mydb.internal:5432

Step 8 — ARG into ENV (the bridge pattern)
# Dockerfile.argenv
FROM alpine

# ARG for build-time value
ARG APP_VERSION=1.0.0

# Promote ARG → ENV so it's available at runtime too
ENV APP_VERSION=$APP_VERSION

CMD ["sh", "-c", "echo running version $APP_VERSION"]

# Build with custom version
docker build -f Dockerfile.argenv \
  --build-arg APP_VERSION=3.1.0 \
  -t myapp:3.1.0 .

# Now available at runtime
docker run --rm myapp:3.1.0
# running version 3.1.0

# Inspect it
docker inspect myapp:3.1.0 | grep APP_VERSION
# "APP_VERSION=3.1.0"

Step 9 — ARG scope (position matters)
FROM alpine

ARG MY_VAR=before   # available from here

RUN echo "before FROM: $MY_VAR"

FROM alpine         # second FROM resets ARG scope!

RUN echo "after second FROM: $MY_VAR"   # empty!

ARG MY_VAR          # must re-declare after each FROM
RUN echo "re-declared: $MY_VAR"         # works now

Step 10 — All 4 combinations tested
FROM alpine

ARG  BUILD_ONLY=build_value       # build only
ENV  RUNTIME_ONLY=runtime_value   # runtime only
ARG  PROMOTED=arg_val
ENV  PROMOTED=$PROMOTED           # both (arg promoted to env)

docker build -t test-all .

# At runtime:
docker run --rm test-all env
# RUNTIME_ONLY=runtime_value   ✓
# PROMOTED=arg_val              ✓ (promoted)
# BUILD_ONLY not shown          ✓ (gone at runtime)

All Interview Questions
CMD vs ENTRYPOINT
Question	Answer
What is the difference between CMD and ENTRYPOINT?	ENTRYPOINT is the fixed executable; CMD provides default args. CMD is easily overridden; ENTRYPOINT requires --entrypoint flag
What happens when you combine both?	ENTRYPOINT runs always; CMD is passed as default args. Runtime args replace CMD but not ENTRYPOINT
What is exec form vs shell form?	Exec form ["cmd"] runs directly as PID 1, receives signals. Shell form cmd runs via /bin/sh -c, your app is NOT PID 1
Why does shell form break graceful shutdown?	SIGTERM goes to sh (PID 1), not your app — app never gets the signal to shut down cleanly
How do you override ENTRYPOINT at runtime?	docker run --entrypoint <new-cmd> <image>
If only CMD is set, what runs?	CMD itself is treated as the full command
Can you have multiple CMD instructions?	Yes, but only the last one takes effect

ARG vs ENV
Question	Answer
What is the difference between ARG and ENV?	ARG is build-time only; ENV persists into the running container
Can ARG be used at runtime?	No — it's gone after the build layer that uses it
How do you make a build-time value available at runtime?	ARG VERSION=1.0 then ENV VERSION=$VERSION — promotes ARG to ENV
Is ENV visible in docker inspect?	Yes — docker inspect shows all ENV values. Never put secrets in ENV
What is the default value syntax for ARG?	ARG NAME=default_value
Does ARG reset after a new FROM in multi-stage?	Yes — must re-declare ARG after each FROM
How do you pass ARG at build time?	docker build --build-arg KEY=value .
Where are ENV variables visible?	In the running container, docker inspect, and all child processes

Combined / Advanced
Question	Answer
Which is better for secrets: ARG or ENV?	Neither — ARG is in build layer history, ENV is in docker inspect. Use BuildKit --mount=type=secret
Can you override ENV at runtime?	Yes — docker run -e KEY=value or --env-file
What is the order of precedence for ENV?	--env-file < -e at runtime (runtime -e wins)
What does CMD ["sh", "-c", "echo $HOME"] do vs CMD ["echo", "$HOME"]?	First: shell expands $HOME ✓. Second: exec form, no shell, $HOME is literal string ✗
A container ignores docker stop and takes 10 seconds to stop — why?	Shell form ENTRYPOINT — sh is PID 1, SIGTERM goes to sh not the app, Docker waits 10s then sends SIGKILL
